{
  "text": "Ϫ channel blockers on rat cerebral arteries using patch-clamp techniques in combination with isobaric and isometric measurements of mechanical activity. The Cl Ϫ channel blockers flufenamic acid and 9-anthracine chloride, which are fairly specific for Ca 2ϩ -activated Cl Ϫ channels, had no effect on myogenic tone, even at high doses. Likewise, glibenclamide, an inhibitor of the cystic fibrosis transmembrane conductance regulator channel (as well as the K ATP channel) was without effect on myogenic tone. 5-Nitro-2-(3-phenylpropylamino)benzoic acid, another Cl Ϫ channel blocker, reversibly inhibited both myogenic tone and KCl-induced tone, but these effects were shown to be mediated by inhibition of VGC channels [CITATION_1] . At this time, the lack of specific blockers does not permit definitive conclusions to be made regarding the role of Cl Ϫ channels in the myogenic response, but the existing evidence suggests they do not play an initiating role.",
